            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How to use the sales tax calculator</h2>
              <p>This sales tax calculator lets you:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Add tax</strong> to a price (net → gross).</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Remove tax</strong> from a total (reverse sales tax).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Find the tax rate</strong> from net and total.</li>
                <li>
                  Handle <strong>multiple line items</strong> with quantities.
                </li>
                <li>Switch currency symbol and rounding precision.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Choose your calculation mode</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add tax to price</strong> – you know the price before
                  tax and the tax rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Remove tax (reverse)</strong> – you know the total
                  including tax and the tax rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Find tax rate</strong> – you know both net and total
                  and want the effective rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Enter tax rate</h3>
              <p>You can either:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Select a <strong>US state preset</strong> (base state rate
                  only), or
                </li>
                <li>
                  Type any <strong>custom tax rate</strong> in the “Tax rate
                  (%)” box.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>If both are filled, the custom rate in the box is used.</p>

              <h3>3. Add your items</h3>
              <p>For each line item, enter:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Price</strong> – per unit price.</li>
                <li><strong>Qty</strong> – quantity of units.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically totals all items and applies the
                tax rate.
              </p>

              <h2>Sales tax formulas</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Add tax to price</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = price before tax (net)</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r \) = tax rate (as a decimal, e.g. 8.25% → 0.0825)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Tax} = P \times r \)</p>
                <p>\( \text{Total} = P \times (1 + r) \)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>2. Remove tax (reverse sales tax)</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( T \) = total price including tax</li>
                  <li>\( r \) = tax rate (decimal)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Net price} = \dfrac{T}{1 + r} \)</p>
                <p>\( \text{Tax} = T - \text{Net price} \)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>3. Find tax rate from net and total</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = price before tax (net)</li>
                  <li>\( T \) = total price including tax</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>\( r = \dfrac{T - P}{P} \)</p>
                <p>As a percentage: \( \text{Rate}(\%) = r \times 100 \).</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Important notes and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Not a filing tool.</strong> This calculator is for
                  planning and estimates only.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rates change frequently.</strong> Always confirm
                  current rates with your state or local tax authority.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Local and special taxes.</strong> Many US locations
                  add city, county, transit, or special district taxes on top of
                  the state rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Taxability varies.</strong> Some items (e.g.
                  groceries, medicine, digital goods) may be taxed differently
                  or exempt.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Example: Texas sales tax calculation</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you sell a taxable item in Texas for $250 and charge
                only the state base rate of 6.25% (ignoring local add-ons):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Tax rate \( r = 6.25\% = 0.0625 \)</li>
                <li>
                  Tax = \( 250 \times 0.0625 = 15.625 \) → $15.63 (rounded to
                  cents)
                </li>
                <li>Total = \( 250 + 15.63 = 265.63 \)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In reality, many Texas locations have combined rates around
                8.25% once local taxes are included, so adjust the rate
                accordingly.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Is sales tax the same as VAT?</h3>
              <p>
                No. <strong>Sales tax</strong> is usually charged only at the
                final retail sale to the consumer. <strong>VAT</strong> (value
                added tax) is charged at each stage of the supply chain, with
                businesses reclaiming input VAT. The formulas for adding and
                removing tax are similar, but legal rules differ.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is only for transaction-based taxes like sales tax
                or VAT-style calculations. For income tax, use a dedicated
                income tax or payroll calculator.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does my effective rate look slightly different?</h3>
              <p>
                Rounding to cents can make the effective rate differ by a few
                hundredths of a percent, especially on small amounts. This is
                normal and usually not a compliance issue.
              </p>
